	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">It looks like someone found the plat generator that's been running lately.  This was posted on EQ's own station boards today, at <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum4/HTML/054137.html" target="_blank">http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/...TML/054137.html</a><br />
<br />
I cannot test it's veracity until I get near a computer.  But if the price changes are right, it looks like the culprit has appeared.<br />
<br />
Edit: I forgot to mention that I edited this persons post somewhat, because it was insanely paranoid, and suggests that someone inside SOE introduced this exploit for their own personal profit.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><br />
Plat Duping - What I am about to describe isn't really "duping". It's more a method of generating lots of cash by buying supplies from NPC vendors, using a tradeskill, then selling them back to NPCs at a profit. The profit generated on a per-item basis may seem low, but when performed hundreds or thousands of times (as is possible with macroing programs) the profit can be astounding.<br />
<br />
Combine<br />
3 small bricks of ore + 1 water = 1 large brick of ore<br />
3 small bricks of medium quality ore + 1 water = 1 large brick of medium quality ore<br />
3 small bricks of high quality ore + 1 water = 1 large brick of high quality ore<br />
<br />
I know what you're going to say. You're going to say you may have done this combine lots of times already so you know there's no profit in it, right?<br />
<br />
Wrong.<br />
<br />
Remember back when the price of a water flask dropped from 1sp to 5cp? Well what you may not know is that lots of other items also had their prices changed. The price of the small brick of medium quality ore was dropped down to 1sp each. <br />
<br />
1 small brick of medium quality ore = 1sp<br />
1 large brick of medium quality ore = 6pp when sold to NPC vendor<br />
<br />
That's almost total profit on 1 combine, and it's a simple combine too, requiring a blacksmithing skill of no more than 36 or so before it is trivial.<br />
<br />
The best part? The MQ ore vendors sell unlimited quantities. The HQ ore is a limited supply but generates higher profit.<br />
<br />
Conversion Profits<br />
Regular ore: Cost of supplies = 1pp, Profit = 3pp when sold<br />
MQ ore: Cost of supplies = 4sp, Profit = 6pp when sold<br />
HQ ore: Cost of supplies = 6pp, Profit = 10pp when sold.<br />
<br />
If you have a macroing program, the MQ ore can generate literally thousands of plat per hour for you while you sit and watch.<br />
</td></tr></table></font></p>
	
	<p><p><img src="/forums/images/sig_separator.gif" width="282" height="11" Alt="Hey! Watch where you point that thing!"><br>
