	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 12-05-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">12:25 AM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">It's a matter of scale, Numo.  These kind of things creep in, unintentionally, from time to time, and it used to be possible to level to some degree in pottery, while making a profit off of large jars sold to vendors, or somesuch.<br />
<br />
But the problem isn't when Bob_the_Noob or Jane_the_Potter does it.  <br />
<br />
It's when 1337_teh_H4xx0r uses a macro program, which is against the EULA in and of it self, to do it 10-15 times a minute, for hours on end.<br />
<br />
At 6pp profit for all vendor buyable items, when you don't even have to write a path macro to walk you to a Pottery wheel (there are a number of Ore vendors within arms reach of a Forge) you can make 60-90pp a minute, 3600pp or so an hour.<br />
<br />
Totally impossible for someone not willing to circumvent the EULA with an external macro program, or engage in speedclicking at a rate guaranteed to net carpal tunnel in an hour.  But with a macro program, once made, someone could generate platinum at a positively stupid rate.<br />
<br />
That's when it becomes an exploit.  When the software is abused with external code not authorized by sony, that lets someone bypass the limits of reason set by the Click click click combine nature of the game, and generate a modest profit repetitively.<br />
<br />
And while we're familiar with pudding guys story, the problem is that in this case there probably isn't just one pudding guy.  It's probably hundreds of pudding guys, all operating under the radar, because no one has to check off the labels, no one has to approve the miles, no one has to even know he's doing it.  <br />
<br />
It's sad that this is the reason that low end tradeskills can't turn a profit... it's just too open to abuse.   But with the already ridiculous rate at which plat flows into Norrath (without flowing out) an abusable feature like this needs to be stopped.<br />
<br />
Oh, and one point, before people think that I'm spelling doomsday here...  remember that artificial economies always find some basic way to work.  As it says in the thread I referenced above, platinum is already quickly becoming a useless commodity... the best high end gear is no drop, and the expensive dropppable gear is usually used to twink out alts.  Adventure points are more valuable, and impossible to farm in such a simplistic way.  <br />
<br />
Chances are if platinum does spiral out of control the OP of this jibber jabber will find a different way to make his living off of our entertainment.  You won't see as much bazaar activity, but you'll start to get a barter economy, as was seen in Diablo II, with the SoJ economy.   Items that were valueless and easy to create, and cumbersome to work with (gold) were ignored in favor of a standard of economy that was feasible... Stones of Jordan.  <br />
<br />
It wouldn't surprise me at all to see something like that.  <br />
<br />
But I'd like to buy my horse first.  <img src="images/smilies/cool.gif" border="0" alt="Cool"></font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
	</td></tr></table>
